1) User test code layer

This is the layer where automation engineers write their test scripts using Playwright APIs.

🔹 Supported Languages
JavaScript / TypeScript (native)
Java
Python
.NET

2️⃣ Playwright Client API Layer

This layer exposes the public API used in tests. It abstracts the complexity of browser communication.

| Class              | Responsibility                |
| ------------------ | ----------------------------- |
| `Browser`          | Represents a browser instance |
| `BrowserContext`   | Provides isolated sessions    |
| `Page`             | Represents a browser tab      |
| `Frame`            | Handles iframes               |
| `Locator`          | Robust element selection      |
| `Request/Response` | Network interception          |

3️⃣ Playwright Driver Layer (Node.js)

The driver acts as the central orchestrator. It receives commands from the client API and communicates with the browsers.

🔹 Responsibilities
Manages browser lifecycle
Handles sessions and contexts
Implements auto-waiting and synchronization
Coordinates communication with browser protocols
Manages events (network, console, dialogs)

| File                | Purpose              |
| ------------------- | -------------------- |
| `browser.ts`        | Browser management   |
| `browserContext.ts` | Context isolation    |
| `page.ts`           | Page orchestration   |
| `frameManager.ts`   | Frame hierarchy      |
| `networkManager.ts` | Network interception |

4️⃣ Communication Layer (Protocols)
🔹 Chromium – Chrome DevTools Protocol (CDP)
Playwright communicates with Chromium using CDP.
Enables deep browser control like network interception, tracing, and emulation.
🔹 Firefox & WebKit – Custom Protocols
Playwright uses patched versions of Firefox and WebKit.
Custom protocols provide consistent cross-browser behavior.
🔹 Transport Mechanism
Communication occurs over WebSockets or pipes.
Messages are exchanged in JSON-RPC format.

5️⃣ Browser Layer

| Browser  | Protocol | Notes                       |
| -------- | -------- | --------------------------- |
| Chromium | CDP      | Includes Chrome and Edge    |
| Firefox  | Custom   | Patched by Playwright       |
| WebKit   | Custom   | Enables Safari-like testing |

🧪 Playwright Test Runner Architecture

| Feature    | Description                            |
| ---------- | -------------------------------------- |
| Workers    | Parallel execution                     |
| Fixtures   | Reusable test setup                    |
| Hooks      | `beforeAll`, `afterEach`, etc.         |
| Assertions | Jest-like `expect`                     |
| Reporters  | HTML, JSON, JUnit                      |
| Retries    | Automatic re-execution of failed tests |

Fixtures : Fixtures are pre-defined objects that Playwright provides to your tests automatically so you don’t have to manually set them up.

✅ Most Important Built-in Fixtures

🥇 1. page : Represents a single browser tab
🥈 2. browser : Entire browser instance (Chromium, Firefox, WebKit)
🥉 3. context : Browser context (like an incognito session)
🧪 4. request : Used for API testing
🎯 5. testInfo : Gives metadata about current test
⚙️ 6. browserName : Current browser name
🌐 7. baseURL :  From config
🧾 8. playwright : Gives access to Playwright APIs
